In rare decay searches the capability of improving the experimental sensitivity depends on the use of intense beams and high performance detectors, accurately calibrated and monitored. This is the only way to ensure that the beam characteristics and the detector performances are reached and maintained over the experiment lifetime. To that purpose several complementary approaches have been developed with some of the methods requiring dedicated beams and/or auxiliary detectors. Many of them have been introduced and commissioned in MEG and will be inherited by MEG II with some modifications to match the upgrade. In addition new methods are introduced to meet the increased complexity of the new experiment.Fig. 4
