The basic requirements for a MEG stopping target are six-fold:
a high muon stopping density over a limited axial region centred on the COBRA fiducial volume,
minimisation of multiple Coulomb scattering for the outgoing positrons,
minimisation of photon conversions from RMD in the target,
minimisation of positron AIF or bremsstrahlung with photons entering the detector acceptance,
allow reconstruction of the positron decay vertex and initial direction at the vertex, onto the target plane and
mechanically stable with good planarity and remotely movable for compatibility with calibrations requiring other targets.Owing to the thinner target, smaller angle for MEG II and the increased Δpμ+/pμ+\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\varDelta p_\mathrm {\mu ^+}/p_\mathrm {\mu ^+}$$\end{document}, the remaining variable material budget consisting of degrader and COBRA helium environment, must then be matched to give an optimal residual range at the target. Figure 16 shows the simulation results for the optimal stopping efficiency versus degrader thickness for the previous MEG 205μm\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
