				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\times $$\end{document} 4 cm3\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\hbox {cm}^{3}$$\end{document} dimensions) each of which read out by fine mesh PMTs at both ends [113]. It showed a good intrinsic time resolution of 40 ps in beam tests, but the operative time resolution on the experimental floor was measured to be σte+∼70ps\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\sigma _{t_{\mathrm {e}^{+}}} {\sim }70{\hbox { ps}}$$\end{document}. The main causes of the degradation were:
a large variation of the optical photon paths originating from the large size of the scintillator (long longitudinal propagation and incident-angle dependence due to its thickness),
a degradation of the PMT performance in the MEG magnetic field,
the error of timing alignment among the bars (time calibration) and
the electronic time jitter.The sum of all these contributions accounted for the above mentioned operating timing resolution.

We plan to overcome such limitations by a detector based on a new concept: a highly segmented scintillation counter. In the new configuration, the 30 scintillator bars are replaced by 512 small scintillation tiles; we call the new detector pixelated timing counter (pTC). There are several advantages in this design over the previous one:
The single counter can easily have a good time resolution due to the small dimensions.
The hit rate of each counter is under control to keep the pile-up probability as well as the ‘double-hit’ probability negligibly low.
Each particle’ s time is measured with many counters to significantly improve the total time resolution.
A flexible detector layout is possible to maximise the detection efficiency and the hit multiplicity.The third point is of particular importance: by properly combining the times measured by Nhit\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
