				\begin{document}$${\mu ^+ \rightarrow \hbox {e}^+ \gamma }$$\end{document} signal events are not compromised. For example, a 5 mm error in the measured position of the photon in the LXe photon detector would result in a signal event possibly being missed because it would not be consistent with being emitted opposite to the direction of the positron. The relative alignment of the LXe photon detector and the spectrometer is implemented using optical survey techniques. For the LXe photon detector, the survey is complicated by the fact that the photo-sensors (SiPMs) are not visible once the LXe photon detector is closed and that their positions relative to the external survey markers change due to thermal contraction and buoyant forces as the LXe photon detector is cooled and filled with liquid xenon.

